                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="verdana" size="2" color="white"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="1" face="trebuchet ms,tahoma" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The fact is that a wiz has a chance to double the entire spell output of a spell. In order to do the same damage I would need to crit every tick. To be honest that what should be done. When a spell is cast see if it crits then double EVERY tick. It would not be over powering as I still have to wait the spell duration to do the max damage.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></font id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"><br /><br />The above is a fallacy. Given the SAME chance to crit, and spells that do the same damage, you will OVER TIME do the same damage.<br /><br />Wiz has a nuke for 3000. He crits 50% of the time. Every 2 nukes he will do 3k + 6k (crit) = 9k damage.  Average damage per nuke will be 4.5k.<br /><br />Necro has a DoT for 3000. He crits 50% of the time on each tick. The DoT takes 10 ticks to run. On an average set of 2 casts of that DoT back to back, he will get 10 ticks at 300 (3k damage) and 10 ticks at 600 (6k damage). Total damage is the SAME 9k. Average damage per DoT is 4.5k, as above.<br /><br />Where the difference is, the Wiz could possibly get both nukes off on the same mob. We would take 2 minutes (20 ticks) to do the same damage. The issue is one of perceived utility. <br /><br />Where the issue arises is that not only are we affected in terms of damage attained when a DoT fails to run for full duration, but also, the effectiveness of any crits is also lessened proportionally. In essence if a Dot runs for half duration, we only get half (statistically) the crits. Whereas if a DD lands for full, they get full benefit of that crit RIGHT THEN. This could be considered analagous to if a DD is partially resisted, they only get a crit based on the base damage of that partial resist.<br /><br />In other words, we're once again running into the addage that DoTs are for boss mobs and other long duration encounters, and simply aren't as flexible as DD's. The AA reflects again that "necros are long term damage", and suffer in the short term. We're wanting Critical affliction to be a wow factor, have all the ticks crit, we're looking for a short term boost, when what we're getting is a long term statistical boost.</span id="msg"></font></td>
                    </tr>
